title: For Sale:   500 rds. Black Hills Mod1 OTM 5.56x45mm  NATO .223 77 Grain Sierra MatchKing Hollow Point - Credit Cards Accepted
postcontent:
500 rounds, ten 50 round boxes. Will not split up.

A rare lot of some of the most sought after 5.56/.223 ammo in the world. If you don't know anything about it, this is what the military elite snipers use and it is far more than a standard bullet. See review below and ask any questions you may have.

http://www.shootingtimes.com/2012/03/21/special-forces-to-civilians-black-hills-mk-262-mod-1-review/

Credit cards accepted (with proper ID - add 3.5%)

Call, text or e-mail REDACTED

Black Hills produces factory new ammunition equal to some of the best handloads and is quickly becoming one of most popular manufacturers of ammunition. Used primarily by all branches of the United State military, this ammunition is also used by competitive shooters and hunters. This 5.56 load was developed for AR-15 platform firearms.

MatchKing rifle bullets are super-accurate bullets with very thin jackets and are held to exacting tolerances in diameter and weight. Their accuracy has been acclaimed worldwide and they have been used to win more target competitions than all target bullets from other manufacturers combined. Each bullet is designed with a very small meplat in order to achieve the highest ballistic coefficient possible. This ammunition is new production, non-corrosive, in boxer primed, reloadable brass cases.

Please Note: While the 5.56x45mm NATO will fit in a .223 Remington chamber, the 5.56 is a military round that runs at higher pressures than its .223 counterpart and is not recommended to be fired in a .223 Remington chamber.

Technical Information
Caliber: 5.56x45mm NATO
Bullet Weight: 77 Grains
Bullet Style: Sierra MatchKing Hollow Point
Case Type: Brass


Ballistics Information:
Muzzle Velocity: 2750 fps
Muzzle Energy: 1293 ft. lbs.

title: For Sale:  9mm for sale 6 boxes/300rds
location: just north of omaha near cunningham lake, Omaha, Nebraska
postcontent:
I bought more than I needed at the last gun show, shot a few hundred rounds, decided 9mm is too small for me, ended up selling my 9mm and buying a .45 instead. Turns out I'm basically one of those bigger is better type people when it comes to guns, so don't think I'll be shooting much 9mm any more, selling off the 6 extra boxes (50 rounds in each box) I have at $24 each, this is at cost so I can get my money back and the ammo doesn't go to waste during these hard times. 

This is very high quality ammo, unlike the other eastern European ammo PPU is brass cased and is of super high quality (arguably better than most American brass), you might know them also as Privi Partisan, their brass is used by Hornady for much of their super premium hunting ammo and some of their 'critical defense' line of premium self defense ammo, Graf & Sons also uses PPU brass for much of their custom ammo line, Wolf uses PPU brass for their "Wolf Gold" premium line of brass cased hunting ammo. 

If your a reloader, you might be interested to know that PPU's brass is of such quality that the legendary Norma line from Olin/Winchester sometiems uses PPU brass instead of brass from Winchester, that means that for some calibers in their super premium norma line the Winchester corporation actually chooses to use PPU as a subcontractor over creating their own brass. In my reloading I often try to use PPU for my medium/high power rifle cartridges over other brands, because the brass is a higher quality alloy when compared to some, is often substantantially thicker than most and the case necks are annealed to a higher standard that any other company I know of because unlike other companies PPU creates their brass products with reloaders specifically in mind. If you reload you probably know what I'm talking about and realize that a thicker case means more reuses before case web/head seperation and a thicker shoulder/better annealing means you can get more reuses from each case before you get cracks in the neck/shoulder area. 

If you don't reload, then all you need to know is that PPU ammo is great stuff, definitely better than Winchester white box, almost as good as Fiocchi, but not quite as amazing as Sellier&Bellot. 

Also willing to trade for .22lr (depending on what it is and its age), most any .17 HMR, some other centerfire ammo, or for reloading supplies/equipment, especially bullets in certain cals, IMR4064, WIN231/HP38, and any primers.

title: For Sale/Trade:  Question about your safety when dealing arms w/no FFL
postcontent:
I read today in an Alton IL newpaper that an Illinois man from Wood River got probation after being charged with dealing firearms with no FFL.  His wife got sick (cancer) and died and with medical bills he had to sell his collection of up to 100 guns to pay taxes on his properties.   He got probation and had to surrender the firearms he still had.     
To my understanding you can sell in Illinois as a private party to another private party as long as both parties have a FOID card. Thats what I found on line anyway. 
This guy was tried in federal court.  So did the feds come in and over rule the state laws and made this guys life suck even worse than it already was?    

So any tips on what not to do or what is lawful?   I thought a bill of sale was all you needed in Missouri and FOID card in Illinois with a BOS.
